\pard\plain \ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 In contemporary architectural paradigms, models are being used as first class citizens to the architectures, MDA, IEEE-1471 and ISP RM/ODP alike. It is therefore imperative to decide upon the major characteristics of a model. A in-depth treatise of models, meta-models, modelling languages and ontologies can be found in [@Henderson-Sellers2012], where the authors identify 6 modes of a model, derived from three dichotomies: the type vs. token modes, the forward- vs. backward-looking modes, and the ontological vs. linguistic modes, as follows.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 * Type models represent different categories that exist in the modelled world, whilst token models represent the individuals from the modelling world that are of interest. This distinction essentially represent the }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 universals -- particulars}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  dichotomy as identified in the ontological square (refer to \\cref\{fig:onto-square-and-sextet\}). As a result, the relationship that is instantiated with its modelled world by a type model is an }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 instance-of}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  relationship, while for a token model this is an }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 equivalence}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  relationship;}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 * The distinction between descriptive and prescriptive models is broadly accepted, where a prescriptive model is used to }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 specify}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  its subject, and a descriptive model is used to }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 describe}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  its subject. As explained by [@Gonzalez-Perez2007], a specification model generally takes a }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 forward-looking}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  role, specifying how the subject is supposed to be. A descriptive model, on the other hand, generally takes a }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 backward-looking}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  role and addresses the subject as it currently is, or once has been. We observe that the characteristics of the }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 refers-to}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  relation become declarative for a forward-looking model whereas they become descriptive for a backward-looking model. Therefore, the refers-to relation is a causal relation, the direction of which is dependent on the model\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s characteristic. This is consequential for the location of the truth of a model: For forward-looking models their truth lies in their meta-models. Mutatis mutandis, the truth for backward-looking models lies in the entities they describe. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 * The distinction between ontological and linguistic mode of a modelling was first coined by [@Atkinson2003]. The distinction often refers to meta-models and ontologies. Essentially, it is about the confusion that emerges between relationships that model }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 instance-of}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  relations (a particular tree that gives rise to a universal Tree), }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 categorisation}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  relations (one or more criteria determine the group an individual belongs to, e.g., evergreens versus deciduous trees) and }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 generalisation}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  relations (a taxonomic hierarchy, e.g., in the Linnaean system of classification an oak belongs to }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 family:Fagaceae}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 , }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 order:Fagales, subclass:Hamamelididae}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 , etc., up to }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 kingdom:Plantae}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 ). Linguistic meta-modelling assumes OMG\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s four layer MOF hierarchy; for each of the adjacent pair of layers the meta layer is considered to model the types that the lower layer can apply in its own model. Adjacent layers are therefore connected though a type-instance relationship, denoted as }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 linguistic instance-of}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  but better relabelled }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 conforms-to}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  [@Bezivin2004; Favre2004a] in order to prevent ambiguities by overloading the }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 instance-of}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  label. Contrarily, ontological meta-modelling acknowledges only one single genuine }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 instance-of}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  relationship between the universals and their individuals. At the DoI, the conceptualisation also recognises subsets of supersets, which translates to the generalisation relationship [@Kuhne2006]. Although the author clearly identifies in [@Atkinson2003; and @Atkinson2011] the necessity for both modes of modelling, the method of their integration is not without issues [@Henderson-Sellers2012]. We follow the latter in their method of integrating both modelling modes.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
